  <info>
    <title>Supported file systems and storage configurations</title>
    <!-- can be changed via merge in the assembly -->
    <!--add author's email address-->
    <meta name="maintainer" content="daria.vladykina@suse.com" its:translate="no"/>
    <abstract>
      <!-- can be changed via merge in the assembly -->
      <para>
        &suselinux;&nbsp;16.0 ships with kernel 6.12 and removes several legacy subsystems and file
        systems. If your environment relies on deprecated kernel features or file systems such as
        <systemitem>quota v1</systemitem>, <systemitem>cgroups v1</systemitem> or
        <systemitem>reiserfs</systemitem>, plan your migration accordingly before upgrading.
      </para>
    </abstract>
  </info>
  <section xml:id="migration-kernel-version">
    <title>What is the default kernel version and which subsystems were removed?</title>
    <para>
      &suselinux;&nbsp;16.0 ships with kernel version 6.12. The following kernel subsystems have
      been removed:
    </para>
    <itemizedlist>
      <listitem>
        <para>
          <systemitem>quota v1</systemitem>
        </para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
        <para>
          <systemitem>cgroups v1 interface</systemitem>
        </para>
      </listitem>
    </itemizedlist>
  </section>
  <section xml:id="migration-filesystem-support">
    <title>Which file systems are supported?</title>
    <para>
      The following table provides an overview of the file system status in &suselinux;&nbsp;16:
    </para>
    <table frame="all">
      <title>File system support status</title>
      <tgroup cols="2">
        <colspec colname="filesystem"/>
        <colspec colname="status"/>
        <thead>
          <row>
            <entry>File system</entry>
            <entry>Status in &suselinux;&nbsp;16</entry>
          </row>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <row>
            <entry>btrfs</entry>
            <entry>Supported&mdash;default file system</entry>
          </row>
          <row>
            <entry>xfs</entry>
            <entry>Supported</entry>
          </row>
          <row>
            <entry>ext2/3/4</entry>
            <entry>Supported</entry>
          </row>
          <row>
            <entry>gfs2</entry>
            <entry>Supported&mdash;both read and write operations.
                            Available on &slehaa; only.</entry>
          </row>
          <row>
            <entry>ocfs2</entry>
            <entry>Dropped. Use gfs2 instead (available only on &slehaa;).</entry>
          </row>
          <row>
            <entry>reiserfs</entry>
            <entry>Dropped</entry>
          </row>
          <row>
            <entry>hfsplus</entry>
            <entry>Dropped</entry>
          </row>
          <row>
            <entry>UFS</entry>
            <entry>Dropped</entry>
          </row>
          <row>
            <entry>quota v1</entry>
            <entry>Dropped</entry>
          </row>
        </tbody>
      </tgroup>
    </table>
  </section>
  <section xml:id="migration-kdump-configuration">
    <title>How to configure Kdump using the command line</title>
    <para>
      In &slea;&nbsp;15, Kdump was configured through &yast;. With &yast; no longer available, use
      the <systemitem>kdumptool</systemitem> command-line tool. Configure Kdump via the following
      variables in <filename>/etc/sysconfig/kdump</filename>:
    </para>
    <itemizedlist>
      <listitem>
        <para>
          KDUMP_CRASHKERNEL
        </para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
        <para>
          KDUMP_UPDATE_BOOTLOADER
        </para>
      </listitem>
    </itemizedlist>
    <para>
      The <systemitem>kdumptool</systemitem> utility can check whether the running kernel has the
      expected crashkernel settings, update the boot loader configuration, and disable kdump by
      removing crashkernel settings from the boot loader.
    </para>
  </section>
</topic>
